english:
  title: A Repudiation of Malevolent Spirits
  author: Lee Chaem
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long heard that the virtue of spirits lies solely in rectitude. The heavens and earth that cover and sustain all things, the sun and moon that shine upon us, the four seasons that turn in their courses, the flourishing of human and animal life, the blooming and withering of grass and trees—all of these flow from the circulation of righteous vital force.

    But whence comes this malevolent force of which you speak? After the age of the ancient sages, the world grew muddled and shallow. The people harbored resentment, heaven grew angry, and the harmonious vital force was wounded. Thus disease was born, striking mortals unexpectedly, causing them pain. Yet I confess I do not understand its origin.

    But now, with ruler and ministers, with all the officials dispensing justice and punishment—rewarding the virtuous and punishing the wicked, guiding this people toward heaven's truths, bringing all into an age of peace—how can malevolent force now wander this world? Whence does it spring?

    The great mountains and mighty rivers that bestow blessings and grace upon the realm are recorded in the sacred calendar and cannot deceive. How dare you, mere malevolence, presume to equal them? In the humble lanes and alleys, ignorant folk engage in foolish acts. When they are touched by your influence and run to shamans and healers, they waste their fortunes and ruin their houses. Such wickedness deserves to be cast beyond the blue vastness, unfit to dwell between heaven and earth.

    In the third month, the heavens hung heavy and dark; vapors from river and mountain drifted endlessly across all quarters. Then you seized upon my weakness and wounded my back and loins. Yet I have left you untreated until now—I do this to observe the full measure of your evil before I strike you down.

    In my youth I studied the way of the sages; I have come to understand the principles that govern both the seen and unseen worlds. How dare you deceive me? I once served the royal court and rose to the rank of the sixth grade—already looked upon by the people. How dare you demean me? Now I hold my aspirations high and admire the contentment of the righteous ones of old. How dare you insult me? Yet you come and go in sudden gusts, bringing cold and heat, deceiving even the virtuous. What heart drives you to this?

    Once, when Cangjie devised writing, spirits wept in the night. When Han Yu rebuked fever, fever dared not afflict him. Both feared the power of words to condemn them. The Duke of Zhou, with all his talents and arts, could commune with spirits because the sage and heaven and earth were one in their cosmic fortune. What we call spirits are but the nature and feeling of heaven and earth itself. Thus I know that malevolent force could find no place in the age of the Duke of Zhou.

    The Book of Poetry says: "Transform into demon or fox-spirit and you cannot be perceived." Yet I do not believe this. Though spirits have neither voice nor shadow, their principles are manifest and clear, known to all. To know their principles is to know their nature; to know their nature is to know the spirit itself. The Book of Changes says: "Fill a cart with demons"—meaning that their principles can be grasped and brought near.

    Your principles and nature I have already come to know. Thus you shall be caught by me. You dare not deceive or demean or insult me. Within the compass of my knowledge, you cannot hide. Go now and depart far from me. I consume you now; I consume you and make you nourishment. Have you nothing to ponder in this?
  footnotes:
    - The 'three ages' (三代) refers to the legendary Xia, Shang, and Zhou dynasties, considered the golden age of Chinese civilization under virtuous rulers.
    - The author held the rank of Jeong Yuk-pum (正六品), the sixth rank in the Joseon official hierarchy, indicating a position of considerable respect and learning.
    - Cangjie (蒼頡) is a legendary figure in Chinese tradition credited with inventing writing. The reference draws on a classical trope of writing's supernatural power.
    - Han Yu (韓愈), known as Tuizhiweng (退之) by courtesy name, was a Tang dynasty poet and philosopher famous for his rationalism and moral courage.
    - The Duke of Zhou (周公旦) was venerated in Confucian tradition as an exemplary sage and minister whose virtue allowed him to commune with spirits.
    - The quoted lines are from the Classic of Poetry (詩經) and the Book of Changes (周易), foundational Confucian texts that the author invokes to support his argument about the nature of spirits and their subordination to righteous principle.
